"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 1 Samuel chapters 9–12
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-1samuel-9-12-fill.py

Christological trajectory:
- Ch9: The seeking-and-finding pattern; the anointed king as YHWH's response to
       his people's cry; the reserved meal as messianic-banquet anticipation
- Ch10: The first royal anointing (māšaḥ → messiah/christ); the Spirit-anointing
        and transformation; royal acclamation; king rejected by worthless men
- Ch11: Spirit-empowered judge-king deliverer; coronation mercy as type of
        messianic pardon; peace-offering coronation feast
- Ch12: Samuel's integrity as type of the righteous judge; salvation-history
        recitation; the conditional covenant fulfilled in Christ; intercession type

Classification levels used:
- direct: NT explicitly cites this verse for Christ
- type: OT person/event structurally anticipates Christ
- shadow: broader pattern points forward less directly
- theme: shared theological vocabulary the NT builds on
- revelation of God: reveals divine character expressed fully in Christ
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>The theme of divine election operates here. Kish is &ldquo;a man of great standing&rdquo; (<em>gibbôr ḥayil</em>) — a qualifier for social standing and military valor. The Benjaminite genealogy grounds Saul in the smallest tribe of Israel, a detail the narrative will emphasize (v21). The trajectory from small tribe to anointed king prefigures the pattern of divine election: God consistently chooses the smaller, the less impressive, the overlooked. The ultimate expression of this pattern is the Incarnation — the King of kings born in an obscure province, in a manger, of a lineage that ran through Bethlehem rather than Jerusalem&rsquo;s court.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A shadow: Saul&rsquo;s physical perfection — &ldquo;no one among the Israelites was more handsome; from his shoulders up he stood taller than all the people&rdquo; — establishes the external standard for kingship that will be explicitly rejected when David is chosen (16:7: &ldquo;man looks at the outward appearance, but the LORD looks at the heart&rdquo;). Saul embodies the kind of king the people desired — impressive, tall, conventionally kingly. The Servant of Isaiah 53:2 has &ldquo;no beauty or majesty to attract us to him, nothing in his appearance that we should desire him.&rdquo; The true Anointed One inverts Saul&rsquo;s standard entirely. Height above others becomes descent below all — the King who stoops to wash feet (John 13:5).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The theme of providential searching runs through the biblical narrative. Saul goes looking for lost donkeys and finds a kingdom. The same providential pattern is explicit in Jacob&rsquo;s sons going to Egypt for grain and finding Joseph; in Ruth going to glean in Boaz&rsquo;s field. The great reversal — the seeker becomes the found — is the structure of grace. Christ&rsquo;s parables of the lost sheep, the lost coin, and the lost son (Luke 15) all enact this reversal: what was lost is found by the one who seeks. The Father &ldquo;goes out&rdquo; to meet the returning prodigal; YHWH sends Samuel to intercept Saul on his way to nowhere important.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The theme of persistence through fruitless searching. Saul traverses multiple regions without finding the donkeys — Ephraim, Shalisha, Shalim, Benjamin. The futility of the search before divine appointment is thematically parallel to human searching apart from God: effort without arrival. The disciples fishing all night and catching nothing (John 21:3) follows the same pattern — exhausted, fruitless labor followed by the encounter with Christ that transforms everything. Providence operates not in spite of the fruitless search but through it.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s practical reasoning — &ldquo;let&rsquo;s go back, or my father will stop worrying about the donkeys and start worrying about us&rdquo; — is interrupted by the servant&rsquo;s suggestion about the man of God. The divine appointment arrives at the moment of turning back. Canonically, this is the structure of encounter with the prophetic word: when human initiative is exhausted, the divine word arrives. Christ&rsquo;s encounters follow this pattern — the disciples are ready to give up on the night&rsquo;s fishing (John 21:3), the Emmaus disciples have given up on their hope (&ldquo;we had hoped that he was the one&rdquo;, Luke 24:21) at the very moment Christ reveals himself.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The servant&rsquo;s description of Samuel — &ldquo;a man of God, a man of distinction whose every word proves true&rdquo; (<em>ʾîš ʾelōhîm nibbād... kol ʾăšer yəḏabbēr bōʾ yāḇōʾ</em>) — anticipates the criterion for true prophecy in Deut 18:22 and points forward to the Prophet greater than Samuel (Deut 18:15). Samuel&rsquo;s every word coming true is the attribute that the NT applies to Christ&rsquo;s word: &ldquo;Heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will never pass away&rdquo; (Matt 24:35). The reliable prophetic word that never fails is fulfilled absolutely only in Christ, the Word incarnate (John 1:14).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The question of what gift to bring the man of God — and the servant&rsquo;s quarter-shekel as the only available offering — is a shadow of the empty-handed coming to Christ that the gospel requires. Saul and his servant have nothing worthy to offer; yet they are received, fed at the head of the table, and given the kingdom. The grace-structure here anticipates the gospel pattern: those who come to Christ with nothing are given everything. The parable of the wedding banquet (Matt 22) precisely inverts the gift-logic: the guests are invited without bringing gifts; the feast is provided entirely by the host.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The servant&rsquo;s quarter-shekel is a small thing offered in faith — all that was available, given without hesitation. The theme of small offering made in faith that opens divine provision runs through Scripture: the widow&rsquo;s two mites (Mark 12:42-44), the boy&rsquo;s five loaves and two fish (John 6:9), the jar of oil that multiplies (2 Kgs 4:2-6). The NT principle that giving what you have in faith — even when it is little — unlocks divine multiplication is foreshadowed here.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The editorial note about the transition from &ldquo;seer&rdquo; (<em>rōʾeh</em>) to &ldquo;prophet&rdquo; (<em>nābîʾ</em>) marks a shift in prophetic office that points toward the one Prophet who fulfills both roles — and more. The seer sees what is hidden; the prophet speaks what YHWH commands. Christ is the one in whom all prophetic vision and speech are unified: he sees the Father (John 6:46), speaks the Father&rsquo;s words (John 12:49-50), and is himself the Word (John 1:1). The entire succession of prophetic office — from seer to prophet to Christ — is a preparation for the one in whom all prophecy finds its voice.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The theme of going to meet the one who has been prepared — Saul goes to the city not knowing Samuel has already been told he is coming. YHWH had prepared both the encounter and the messenger before Saul arrived. The pre-arranged meeting is a shadow of how the divine initiative always precedes the human response: &ldquo;We love because he first loved us&rdquo; (1 John 4:19). In Christ, the divine preparation is absolute — chosen &ldquo;before the creation of the world&rdquo; (Eph 1:4) to meet humanity at its point of need.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The young women drawing water who direct Saul to Samuel — unnamed, incidental, used providentially to guide Saul to his destiny. The theme of providential guidance through ordinary persons and encounters runs through the Gospels: the Samaritan woman at the well (John 4) points others to Jesus; the disciples are directed to a man carrying a water jar (Luke 22:10). Providence works through the unremarkable and the ordinary to accomplish its purposes.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Samuel has come for the sacrifice at the high place, and the meal is being prepared in anticipation of his arrival. The sequence — the sacrifice, the meal, the honoured guest — prefigures the structure of covenant fellowship: sacrifice first (atonement), then meal (communion). This is the pattern of the Passover (sacrifice and meal), the peace offering, and ultimately the Lord&rsquo;s Supper — instituted at a meal after the sacrifice of Christ is accomplished.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Samuel&rsquo;s blessing before the feast — &ldquo;he pronounces the blessing over the sacrifice; only then do the guests eat&rdquo; — positions Samuel as the one whose blessing sanctifies the meal. Christ is the one whose blessing transforms the common meal into covenant communion: at the Last Supper he took bread, &ldquo;and when he had given thanks, he broke it&rdquo; (1 Cor 11:24). The presiding prophet-priest at the meal who blesses before others eat is the pattern that Christ fulfills in person.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The providential meeting at the gate — the two going in opposite directions who nevertheless arrive at the same moment. Samuel was &ldquo;coming out toward them&rdquo; just as they entered. Divine orchestration of encounters at city gates recurs in the OT: Boaz meets Ruth&rsquo;s kinsman-redeemer at the gate (Ruth 4:1); the man who finds Joseph is &ldquo;wandering in the fields&rdquo; when Joseph has lost his way (Gen 37:15). The Christ who meets us going in the opposite direction — coming toward us while we are heading away — is the pattern of grace that this providential encounter embodies.</p>",
    "15": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s advance disclosure to Samuel — &ldquo;the day before Saul arrived&rdquo; — establishes the pattern of divine foreknowledge preceding election. YHWH did not react to Saul&rsquo;s arrival; he had already told Samuel what was coming. The revelation before the event is the structure of prophetic anticipation: God announces what he will do before he does it (Amos 3:7: &ldquo;the Sovereign LORD does nothing without revealing his plan to his servants the prophets&rdquo;). The ultimate pre-announcement is Christ: foretold throughout the OT before appearing in history. The divine disclosure in advance is a revelation of God as the one who acts sovereignly and then reveals his action rather than reacting to human events.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A direct anticipation: the formula in v16 — &ldquo;I have seen the suffering of my people and their cry has come up to me&rdquo; — directly echoes the Exodus calling (Exod 3:7-9: &ldquo;I have indeed seen the misery of my people... I have heard them crying out... I am concerned about their suffering&rdquo;). The anointing of Saul is framed as a new Exodus: the same divine compassion that sent Moses now sends an anointed king. But the pattern awaits its complete fulfillment in Christ, whose coming is precisely YHWH hearing the cry of a humanity enslaved not merely to political oppressors but to sin and death. The cry of the world that climaxes in the Incarnation is the ultimate fulfillment of the &ldquo;cry has come up to me&rdquo; formula.</p>",
    "17": "<p>YHWH points out Saul to Samuel: &ldquo;Here is the man I told you about — he will govern my people.&rdquo; The divine identification of the elect king is the moment of divine designation. The same pattern occurs at Christ&rsquo;s baptism when the Father identifies him: &ldquo;This is my Son, whom I love; with him I am well pleased&rdquo; (Matt 3:17). The divine finger pointing at the elect king — YHWH identifying his chosen to his prophetic representative — is the inauguration of messianic office. The verb <em>yaʿăṣōr</em> (will govern/restrain) is a limited commission; the one who truly governs without limit is the one of whom Isa 9:7 says &ldquo;of the greatness of his government and peace there will be no end.&rdquo;</p>",
    "18": "<p>Saul asks Samuel where to find the seer — not knowing he is already speaking with the very person he seeks. The irony of the unconscious encounter with the one you were looking for is a shadow of humanity&rsquo;s encounter with Christ: those who asked &ldquo;where can we find God?&rdquo; were already standing in front of him (John 14:9: &ldquo;Anyone who has seen me has seen the Father&rdquo;). The one who asks for directions to the prophet is already at the prophet&rsquo;s feet; the one who seeks God has already been found by him.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Samuel&rsquo;s &ldquo;I am the seer&rdquo; (<em>ʾānōkî hārōʾeh</em>) is the first of the prophet&rsquo;s self-identifications that culminate in Christ&rsquo;s &ldquo;I am&rdquo; statements. Samuel says: I am the one you were looking for; come with me; you will know everything. The structure of the divine self-disclosure — &ldquo;I am what you are seeking; come and you will find more than you imagined&rdquo; — is the deep pattern of every encounter with YHWH and Christ: &ldquo;I am the way, the truth, and the life&rdquo; (John 14:6); &ldquo;I am the resurrection and the life&rdquo; (John 11:25); &ldquo;I am the bread of life&rdquo; (John 6:35).</p>",
    "20": "<p>Samuel&rsquo;s declaration — &ldquo;for whom all Israel desires — is it not you and all your family?&rdquo; — reveals the scale of what Saul is receiving: the desire of the entire people. The nation&rsquo;s longing for a king who will deliver them is concentrated in Saul. The NT frames Christ as the fulfillment of the deepest desire of the nations: &ldquo;the desire of all nations shall come&rdquo; (Hag 2:7 KJV) — the one in whom every longing for justice, peace, and divine presence is satisfied. Saul partially answers the surface desire; Christ answers the desire at its root.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s self-deprecation — &ldquo;I am from Benjamin, the smallest tribe; my family is the least of all Benjamin&rsquo;s clans&rdquo; — is the pattern of the elect responding to divine calling with awareness of their inadequacy: Moses (&ldquo;who am I?&rdquo; Exod 3:11), Gideon (&ldquo;my clan is the weakest in Manasseh&rdquo;, Judg 6:15), Jeremiah (&ldquo;I do not know how to speak; I am too young&rdquo;, Jer 1:6). The theme of the elect being small/least is fulfilled in Christ&rsquo;s Incarnation: the King of the universe coming as a vulnerable infant in Bethlehem of Judah — a small town, a carpenter&rsquo;s family, an obscure province. Paul cites this pattern directly: &ldquo;God chose the weak things of the world to shame the strong&rdquo; (1 Cor 1:27).</p>",
    "22": "<p>Samuel places Saul at the head of the table among the invited guests — the last shall be first, the one who came looking for donkeys is seated at the place of honor. This is the table-reversal that runs through the entire biblical narrative and culminates in Christ&rsquo;s parables (Luke 14:7-11: &ldquo;when you are invited, take the lowest place... for whoever exalts himself will be humbled, and whoever humbles himself will be exalted&rdquo;) and in the messianic banquet where the last invited are brought into the feast (Matt 22:9-10). The unexpected guest given the place of honor is a structural type of grace.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The reserved portion — set aside by divine command before Saul arrived — is a shadow of the messianic preparation. Samuel tells the cook to bring &ldquo;the portion I gave you — the one I told you to set aside.&rdquo; YHWH had prepared the meal for the king-elect before his arrival, just as the kingdom was prepared for Christ &ldquo;from the creation of the world&rdquo; (Matt 25:34). The meal that was held in anticipation of the right guest: &ldquo;I confer on you a kingdom, just as my Father conferred one on me&rdquo; (Luke 22:29).</p>",
    "24": "<p>A shadow of the messianic banquet: the reserved thigh-portion set aside specifically for Saul, presented at the appointed time. Samuel&rsquo;s words — &ldquo;it has been reserved for you... from the time I invited the guests&rdquo; — articulate predestinated provision: before the feast began, the king&rsquo;s portion was kept. The messianic meal in Isaiah 25:6 — &ldquo;on this mountain the LORD Almighty will prepare a feast of rich food for all peoples&rdquo; — is the full realization of what this reserved meal anticipates. Christ at the Last Supper explicitly frames the meal within anticipation of its fulfillment: &ldquo;I will not eat it again until it finds fulfillment in the kingdom of God&rdquo; (Luke 22:16).</p>",
    "25": "<p>Samuel and Saul talking on the rooftop — the private conversation between the prophet and the elect king before the public anointing. The intimate disclosure before the public commission is the pattern of prophetic preparation: YHWH speaks privately before acting publicly. Christ&rsquo;s private preparation with the Father (the prayer in Gethsemane, John 17&rsquo;s high-priestly prayer) precedes his public suffering and glorification. The rooftop conversation — above the common level, between the prophet and the king — is the space of divine-human exchange that the Incarnation makes permanent: &ldquo;We have seen his glory&rdquo; (John 1:14).</p>",
    "26": "<p>The early rising and sending-out continues the pattern of prophetic dispatch. Samuel sending Saul on his way after the private encounter is the model of discipleship commissioning: receive instruction in private, go out in public. The sequence of revelation → private preparation → public sending runs through the NT discipleship pattern (the disciples trained privately with Jesus, then sent out in Acts 1:8). The dawn-rising of the prophet to send the anointed one anticipates the dawn of resurrection: the early morning encounter between the women and the risen Christ (Mark 16:2; John 20:1), after which he sends them out.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The dismissal of the servant so that YHWH&rsquo;s word may be given privately — &ldquo;send the servant on ahead&rdquo; — creates the space for prophetic disclosure to the elect. The private word of God to the chosen one, sealed apart from bystanders, is the pattern of prophetic commissioning: YHWH speaks to Moses apart from the camp, to Elijah alone at Horeb, to Isaiah in his throne-room vision. Christ similarly withdraws for private disclosure: the Transfiguration is shown to three disciples apart from the rest (Matt 17:1); the resurrection appears first in private before the public confirmation. The private word that constitutes the messianic commission is foundational to the public messianic mission.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>A type: the anointing of Saul is the first royal anointing in Israel&rsquo;s history and the inauguration of the messianic institution. The Hebrew root <em>māšaḥ</em> (to anoint) gives both the Hebrew <em>māšîaḥ</em> (Messiah) and, through the LXX translation <em>christos</em> (anointed one), the title Christ. Every royal anointing in the OT is a step in the chain that terminates at Christ&rsquo;s anointing — not with oil on the head, but with the Spirit at his baptism (John 1:32-33: &ldquo;the Spirit came down from heaven as a dove and remained on him... the one on whom you see the Spirit come down and remain is the one who will baptize with the Holy Spirit&rdquo;). Samuel anointing Saul is the prototype; the Father anointing the Son with the Spirit is the fulfillment. Acts 10:38: &ldquo;God anointed Jesus of Nazareth with the Holy Spirit and power.&rdquo;</p>",
    "2": "<p>The first sign given to Saul — the two men at Rachel&rsquo;s tomb — connects to Rachel as a site of mourning and death that anticipates new life. Rachel&rsquo;s tomb (Gen 35:19-20) marked the place of a death in childbirth; it becomes in Jer 31:15 the site of &ldquo;Rachel weeping for her children.&rdquo; Matthew 2:17-18 quotes Jer 31:15 for the massacre of the innocents at Bethlehem. The first sign to the first anointed king begins at a tomb — a shadow of the resurrection pattern: the first and final sign of the true Messiah begins and ends at a tomb. The good news comes from the place of mourning: the donkeys are found; death gives way to life.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The three men going up to God at Bethel — pilgrims carrying worship offerings — encounter the newly anointed king on the road. The anointed king meets worshippers going to God before his public installation. The theme of the anointed one crossing paths with those seeking God runs through the gospel accounts: Christ encounters seekers on roads (the Emmaus disciples, Luke 24:15), at wells (the Samaritan woman, John 4:7), and in the temple (the blind man after healing, John 9:35). Bethel (&ldquo;house of God&rdquo;) was one of Israel&rsquo;s oldest worship sites, associated with Jacob&rsquo;s ladder (Gen 28:12-19); the encounter on the way to God foreshadows Christ as the way to God (John 14:6).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The two loaves of bread given to Saul by the Bethel pilgrims are a small sign of material provision on the journey. The theme of bread provided on the road of messianic calling runs through Scripture: manna in the wilderness, Elijah fed by the angel before his long journey (1 Kgs 19:6-7), and the disciples given food by Christ on Emmaus road. Christ himself is the bread of life (John 6:35); the provision of bread to the anointed one on his commissioning journey is a shadow of the one who both receives and becomes the sustaining bread.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The prophesying company at Gibeah-elohim (&ldquo;hill of God&rdquo;) — playing instruments and prophesying with the Spirit — is an early example of the community of the Spirit that will characterize the messianic age. Joel 2:28-29 (&ldquo;I will pour out my Spirit on all people; your sons and daughters will prophesy&rdquo;) is the eschatological expansion of this pattern, and Acts 2 is its fulfillment. The Spirit&rsquo;s communal manifestation here — not limited to one prophet but moving through a group — prefigures Pentecost, where the Spirit descends on the assembled community rather than on one individual alone.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;the Spirit of the LORD will come powerfully upon you, and you will be changed into a different person&rdquo; (<em>wənehpaktā ləʾîš ʾaḥēr</em> — literally &ldquo;you will be turned into another man&rdquo;). The Spirit&rsquo;s transforming work on the anointed king anticipates the new-creation transformation promised in the new covenant (2 Cor 5:17: &ldquo;if anyone is in Christ, the new creation has come; the old has gone, the new is here&rdquo;). Saul&rsquo;s transformation is temporary and partial — the Spirit will later depart from him (16:14). Christ&rsquo;s Spirit-anointing is permanent (John 1:32: the Spirit &ldquo;remained&rdquo; on him), and the transformation he works in believers is eschatologically complete (Phil 1:6: &ldquo;he who began a good work in you will carry it on to completion&rdquo;).</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;God is with you&rdquo; (<em>hāʾelōhîm ʿimmāk</em>) — the Immanuel formula. The assurance of divine presence given to the newly anointed king is the foundational covenant promise: &ldquo;I will be with you&rdquo; (Exod 3:12; Josh 1:9). The divine presence with the anointed one is the source of his effectiveness. Christ is <em>Immanu-El</em> — &ldquo;God with us&rdquo; — in his very person (Matt 1:23, citing Isa 7:14), and his final commissioning word is &ldquo;I am with you always, to the very end of the age&rdquo; (Matt 28:20). What was a conditional promise to Saul (&ldquo;act as the situation demands — for God is with you&rdquo;) becomes in Christ an unconditional and permanent presence.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The command to wait at Gilgal for Samuel — seven days, until he arrives with sacrifice — is the covenantal test of Saul&rsquo;s obedience that he will fail in ch13. The waiting that leads to acting in God&rsquo;s time rather than one&rsquo;s own is a persistent theme: Abraham waiting 25 years for Isaac, Israel waiting 40 years in the wilderness, the disciples waiting ten days for Pentecost (Acts 1:4: &ldquo;do not leave Jerusalem, but wait for the gift my Father promised&rdquo;). Christ himself waited: 30 years of hidden preparation before his public ministry; 40 days in the wilderness before beginning to preach. The obedient waiting for God&rsquo;s appointed time is the antithesis of Saul&rsquo;s impatient sacrifice.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;God gave him a new heart&rdquo; (<em>wayyahalek-lô ʾelōhîm lēḇ ʾaḥēr</em>) is the language of covenantal inner transformation. The &ldquo;new heart&rdquo; given to Saul at his anointing anticipates the new-covenant promise of Jer 31:33 (&ldquo;I will put my law in their minds and write it on their hearts&rdquo;) and Ezek 36:26 (&ldquo;I will give you a new heart and put a new spirit in you&rdquo;). Saul&rsquo;s new heart does not sustain — he reverts to fear and disobedience. The permanent new heart that Jeremiah and Ezekiel promise is what Christ accomplishes through the Spirit&rsquo;s indwelling (Rom 5:5: &ldquo;God has poured out his love into our hearts by the Holy Spirit&rdquo;). The signs all come true — confirming that YHWH&rsquo;s word is reliable even when the recipient ultimately fails.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Spirit of God coming powerfully upon Saul and his prophesying — placing him in the same Spirit-experience as the prophetic band — is the visible confirmation of anointing. The Spirit&rsquo;s communal manifestation that crosses social boundaries (king with prophets) is the prototype of Pentecost&rsquo;s boundary-crossing: Jews and Gentiles, men and women, old and young, all receiving the Spirit together (Acts 2:17-18 citing Joel 2:28-29). The Spirit&rsquo;s falling on the newly anointed Saul among the prophets is the first scene of what will be a widening river of Spirit-outpouring that reaches its flood at Pentecost.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;Is Saul also among the prophets?&rdquo; — the proverb captures the astonishment at unexpected divine action: the one nobody thought was a prophet is prophesying. The same pattern of shocked recognition recurs with Christ: &ldquo;Who is this? Even the winds and the waves obey him!&rdquo; (Matt 8:27); &ldquo;Where did this man get these things?&rdquo; (Mark 6:2); &ldquo;Is not this the carpenter?&rdquo; (Mark 6:3). Those who knew Jesus from Nazareth were astonished at his authority — the unexpected divine activity in an ordinary person. The question &ldquo;Is Saul also among the prophets?&rdquo; anticipates the ultimate question: &ldquo;Who do you say that I am?&rdquo; (Matt 16:15).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The anonymous questioner&rsquo;s response — &ldquo;And who is their father?&rdquo; — redirects the origin question from human genealogy to divine origin. A prophet&rsquo;s &ldquo;father&rdquo; in the sense of spiritual source is not a human parent but the Spirit of God. The question anticipates the NT controversy over Jesus&rsquo; origin: &ldquo;Is this not the carpenter&rsquo;s son?... Where then did this man get all these things?&rdquo; (Matt 13:55-56). Christ&rsquo;s true &ldquo;father&rdquo; is not Joseph but God (John 1:14; 8:19). The proverb &ldquo;Is Saul also among the prophets?&rdquo; becomes a standing saying about unexpected divine activity — pointing forward to the ultimate surprise of the Incarnation: God himself among the humans.</p>",
    "13": "<p>After prophesying, Saul goes to the high place — the Spirit-anointed king returning to worship. The pattern of Spirit-experience leading to worship is the normative sequence: Pentecost is followed by &ldquo;they devoted themselves to the apostles&rsquo; teaching and to fellowship, to the breaking of bread and to prayer&rdquo; (Acts 2:42). The Spirit&rsquo;s coming produces devotion rather than pride. Christ himself after his anointing at baptism goes into the wilderness — a form of going apart for preparation — before beginning public ministry. The anointed one&rsquo;s movement between Spirit-encounter and the place of meeting God is the rhythm of the messianic life.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s uncle asks where he has been, and Saul gives the surface answer — looking for donkeys — while concealing the deeper reality of his anointing. The concealment of the messianic appointment is a recurring pattern: Christ repeatedly tells people not to speak of his identity until the appointed time (&ldquo;the messianic secret&rdquo; in Mark&rsquo;s Gospel, e.g., Mark 1:44; 5:43; 7:36). The hidden king, the concealed anointing, the appointment not yet made public — these are the marks of the period between election and enthronement. Christ was anointed in history but not yet publicly declared until the resurrection (Rom 1:4: &ldquo;declared to be the Son of God with power... by his resurrection from the dead&rdquo;).</p>",
    "15": "<p>The uncle&rsquo;s pressing question — &ldquo;tell me what Samuel said to you&rdquo; — is the kind of inquiry that seeks the divine word behind the human encounter. The desire to know what the prophet said is the desire for divine disclosure. Every generation&rsquo;s seeking to understand what Christ &ldquo;really said&rdquo; is the same instinct: the encounter that changes everything has a word behind it that others want to access. The disciples&rsquo; question &ldquo;Lord, are you at this time going to restore the kingdom to Israel?&rdquo; (Acts 1:6) is the same pressing question the uncle asks — what exactly was said about the kingdom?</p>",
    "16": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s silence about the kingship (<em>wədaḇar hamməlûkāh lōʾ-higgîd-lô</em>) is notable. He tells the donkey-news but not the kingdom-news. The theme of partial disclosure — some things reported, the central thing concealed — is the pattern of the period of hidden preparation. Christ kept many things private until the appointed time; the parables conceal as well as reveal (&ldquo;the secret of the kingdom of God has been given to you. But to those on the outside everything is said in parables&rdquo;, Mark 4:11). The anointed one&rsquo;s discretion about his mission is part of the divine economy of revelation.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Samuel calls the assembly at Mizpah — the place of covenant before YHWH. Mizpah (&ldquo;watchtower&rdquo;) was one of the principal covenant-assembly sites for Israel (Judg 10:17; 11:11; 20:1,3; 1 Sam 7:5-6). The gathering of all Israel before YHWH for the formal installation of the king mirrors the Sinai assembly — the whole people before God for constitutional covenant action. The NT fulfillment is the new covenant assembly: &ldquo;you have come to Mount Zion... to the church of the firstborn&rdquo; (Heb 12:22-23), the eschatological gathering of all YHWH&rsquo;s people before the heavenly throne.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Samuel&rsquo;s recitation of the Exodus salvation — &ldquo;I brought Israel up out of Egypt and rescued you from the power of Egypt and all the kingdoms that were oppressing you&rdquo; — is the covenant-preamble formula (cf. Exod 20:2; Deut 5:6: &ldquo;I am the LORD your God who brought you out of Egypt&rdquo;). YHWH&rsquo;s identity is established through his saving acts. Christ&rsquo;s identity is similarly established through his salvific action — the new Exodus he accomplishes (Luke 9:31 uses <em>exodon</em> for his death; 1 Cor 5:7: &ldquo;Christ our Passover lamb has been sacrificed&rdquo;). The God of the Exodus who speaks to Samuel is the same God incarnate in Christ who accomplishes the final Exodus from sin and death.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The indictment — &ldquo;you have rejected your God who saves you from every calamity... and said &lsquo;put a king over us&rsquo;&rdquo; — is the theological assessment of the monarchy&rsquo;s foundation: it began in the rejection of YHWH&rsquo;s kingship. The NT frames Christ&rsquo;s rejection similarly: &ldquo;He came to that which was his own, but his own did not receive him&rdquo; (John 1:11). The pattern of YHWH being rejected as king by his own people — first in Samuel&rsquo;s day, finally at the cross (&ldquo;we have no king but Caesar&rdquo;, John 19:15) — is the great irony of the covenant: Israel rejects YHWH as king and asks for a human substitute, then rejects the human-divine King when he actually comes. The institution that began in rejection of YHWH ends in the rejection of YHWH incarnate.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Benjamin chosen by lot — the smallest tribe. Benjamin being chosen first is itself a reversal of expectation (the largest tribe, Judah, might have been expected to produce the king). The lot-choice of Benjamin, the smallest, continues the pattern of divine election of the unexpected (1 Cor 1:27-28: &ldquo;God chose the weak things of the world... the lowly things... the despised things — and the things that are not — to nullify the things that are&rdquo;). The Davidic line that will eventually supersede Saul will come from Judah — the lion&rsquo;s tribe (Gen 49:10) — but even the Davidic messiah is described as coming from Bethlehem, small among Judah&rsquo;s clans (Mic 5:2).</p>",
    "21": "<p>Saul chosen by lot but nowhere to be found — the elected king in hiding. The hidden king who must be sought out is a shadow of the hiddenness of Christ: born in obscurity, unknown to the powerful, hidden in Egypt, raised in Nazareth (&ldquo;can anything good come from there?&rdquo;, John 1:46), unknown to the religious establishment until his public ministry. The chosen king in hiding who must be searched out before he can be installed is the pattern of the Messiah&rsquo;s concealment — present in the world but not yet publicly manifest.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;He has hidden himself among the luggage&rdquo; (<em>hinnēh hûʾ nistāʾ ʾel-hakkelîm</em>) — the king-elect hidden among ordinary things. The theme of the divine hidden in the ordinary runs through the entire biblical narrative and climaxes in the Incarnation: God hidden in human flesh, the King hidden in a carpenter from Nazareth. The kenosis of Phil 2:7 (&ldquo;he made himself nothing, taking the very nature of a servant... he humbled himself&rdquo;) is the theological articulation of what Saul&rsquo;s hiding among the luggage anticipates in miniature — though Saul hides from fear, Christ&rsquo;s condescension was willing and purposeful.</p>",
    "23": "<p>When Saul is brought out of hiding, he stands &ldquo;a head taller than everyone else&rdquo; — the king is revealed by his height, the external mark the people desired. The contrast with Christ&rsquo;s revelation could not be sharper: Christ is revealed not by physical stature but by the Spirit&rsquo;s testimony (John 1:32-34), by his works (John 10:25), and ultimately by his resurrection (Rom 1:4). The people can see Saul&rsquo;s greatness with their eyes; Christ&rsquo;s greatness requires the spiritual sight that the Spirit gives (John 3:3; Matt 16:17: &ldquo;flesh and blood did not reveal this to you, but my Father in heaven&rdquo;).</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;Long live the king!&rdquo; (<em>yĕḥî hammelek</em>) — the first royal acclamation in Israel. The shout of the people for the anointed king is the prototype of the Messianic cry. &ldquo;Hosanna!&rdquo; (&ldquo;save now!&rdquo;) at the Triumphal Entry (Matt 21:9, citing Ps 118:25-26) is the completion of this acclamation for the true Messiah. The crowd in Jerusalem shouts &ldquo;Blessed is the king who comes in the name of the Lord&rdquo; — the royal acclamation that began with Saul finds its object in Jesus. The tragic irony: five days after the Hosanna, the same city shouts &ldquo;Crucify him!&rdquo; — the acclamation giving way to rejection, which itself is the paradox that produces salvation.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Samuel writes down the rights and duties of the kingship (<em>mišpaṭ hamməlûkāh</em>) and deposits it before YHWH — the constitutional document of the monarchy. The written covenant document deposited before YHWH is the pattern of Mosaic covenant: Exod 24:7 (the Book of the Covenant read aloud before the people); Deut 31:26 (the Torah placed beside the ark). The kingdom of Christ is likewise constituted by a covenant word — the new covenant in his blood (Luke 22:20; Heb 8:6-13) — written not on stone or scroll but on the heart (Jer 31:33; 2 Cor 3:3).</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;Men whose hearts God had moved&rdquo; (<em>ḥayil ʾăšer-nāgaʿ ʾelōhîm bəlibbām</em>) accompany Saul — those divinely drawn to the new king. The same pattern surrounds Christ: the disciples are drawn to him by the Father (John 6:44: &ldquo;No one can come to me unless the Father who sent me draws them&rdquo;). Those who follow the king are those whose hearts the Spirit has moved — the same divine action that drew Israel&rsquo;s valiant men to Saul draws sinners to Christ. The formation of a loyal band around the newly installed king anticipates the gathering of the Church around the risen Christ.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The worthless men (<em>bənê bəliyyaʿal</em>) who despise Saul and bring him no gift — saying &ldquo;how is this man going to save us?&rdquo; (<em>mah-yōšîʿēnû zeh</em>) — are the type of those who rejected Christ: &ldquo;He came to that which was his own, but his own did not receive him&rdquo; (John 1:11). The specific question — &ldquo;how will this man save us?&rdquo; — is the question of unbelief about the Messiah. The crowd at the cross echoes it: &ldquo;He saved others... but he can&rsquo;t save himself!&rdquo; (Matt 27:42). Saul&rsquo;s silent response (&ldquo;Saul said nothing&rdquo;) anticipates Christ before his accusers: &ldquo;he did not open his mouth&rdquo; (Isa 53:7; Matt 27:14).</p>"
  },
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>The Ammonite threat against Jabesh-gilead — the besieged city crying out for rescue — is the presenting crisis that occasions Saul&rsquo;s first test as king. The structure is the judge-deliverer pattern: the people under threat → the Spirit comes upon the judge → the deliverer defeats the enemy. Saul as Spirit-anointed deliverer is in the typological sequence: Othniel, Gideon, Samson, Saul, and ultimately Christ — the final Judge who delivers his people not from national enemies but from sin and death. The Jabesh-gilead connection has covenant depth: the men of Jabesh would later honor Saul&rsquo;s body (31:11-13) — this deliverance and that faithfulness bracket Saul&rsquo;s kingship.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Nahash&rsquo;s condition — gouging out every right eye — was a deliberate strategy of shame and military incapacitation: the right eye was the eye used to aim over a shield, so a one-eyed soldier was not merely maimed but militarily neutralized. The threat of public shame and permanent incapacitation for the whole community is the context of the deliverance. Christ&rsquo;s deliverance similarly addresses the shaming and incapacitating effect of sin: he restores sight to the blind, dignity to the shamed, capability to the paralyzed. The healing of the blind man in John 9 is not merely physical — it reverses the shame-structure that the disciples assumed (&ldquo;who sinned, this man or his parents?&rdquo;, v2).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The seven-day delay for seeking help follows the pattern of covenant time-boundaries: the seven-day wait that recurs throughout the OT (Saul&rsquo;s own later waiting, 13:8; mourning periods). The delay is not indecision but the proper protocol for seeking help through legitimate channels. The NT parallel: the disciples are told to wait in Jerusalem for the Spirit (Acts 1:4-5) — the delay between commission and empowerment is not a gap but a preparation. God&rsquo;s timing includes waiting that tests whether the threatened party will seek help in the right place.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The messengers arrive at Gibeah and the whole town weeps — the corporate response of grief to the threat against fellow Israelites. The covenant solidarity that makes another tribe&rsquo;s suffering one&rsquo;s own is the foundation of the messianic community. Christ&rsquo;s tears at Lazarus&rsquo;s tomb (John 11:35) and over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41) are the fullest expression of this covenant solidarity: the deliverer weeps with those whose suffering he is about to address. The town&rsquo;s grief is not hopelessness but the proper response that creates the context for the Spirit&rsquo;s action in v6.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Saul coming in from the field behind his oxen — still in his pre-kingship role as farmer — hears the weeping and asks about it. The newly anointed king who has not yet acted as king is interrupted by the community&rsquo;s need. The pattern of the messianic vocation breaking in on the ordinary life: the disciples are at their fishing and tax-collecting when called; Christ is at a wedding celebration when the wine runs out. The crisis that interrupts ordinary life is the moment of messianic disclosure — the one who seemed like an ordinary person is revealed as the deliverer when crisis demands it.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;the Spirit of God came powerfully upon Saul when he heard those words&rdquo; — the Spirit activating the anointed one in response to the people&rsquo;s need. The Spirit&rsquo;s coming as response to human suffering and need is the pattern of divine compassionate action. Christ&rsquo;s Spirit-anointing is for the same purpose: &ldquo;the Spirit of the Lord is on me, because he has anointed me to proclaim good news to the poor... to set the oppressed free&rdquo; (Luke 4:18, citing Isa 61:1). The Spirit that moves Saul to act on behalf of those threatened is the Spirit that moves Christ to the cross on behalf of all humanity under the threat of death and judgment.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The cut-up oxen sent as a graphic threat/summons — &ldquo;this is what will be done to the oxen of any man who does not march out&rdquo; — is a covenant-curse mechanism: the oath of binding alliance enforced by the threat of dismemberment, the same mechanism as the covenant ceremony of Gen 15 where animals are cut in pieces and the covenanting parties pass between them (the curse of the covenant: &ldquo;may I be like these animals if I break the oath&rdquo;). The terror of the LORD (<em>paḥad YHWH</em>) that falls on the people mobilizes them — the covenant fear that produces covenant obedience. Christ inverts this: it is not the threat of dismemberment but the love demonstrated at the cross that compels his people (2 Cor 5:14: &ldquo;the love of Christ compels us&rdquo;).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The muster at Bezek — 300,000 from Israel and 30,000 from Judah — assembles the whole nation under the newly installed king. The gathering of all Israel for battle under the anointed one anticipates the eschatological gathering of YHWH&rsquo;s people under the Messiah: &ldquo;he will gather his elect from the four winds, from one end of the heavens to the other&rdquo; (Matt 24:31). The two numbers (Israelites and Judahites separately counted) already anticipates the north-south tension that will split into two kingdoms; the day when both assemble under one king is the day of the true Davidic successor (Ezek 37:22: &ldquo;I will make them one nation in the land&rdquo;).</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;By tomorrow at noon you will be rescued&rdquo; — the messenger of salvation delivers the promise of deliverance before it occurs. The gospel is precisely this: the announcement of salvation before its experiential arrival. &ldquo;Today in the town of David a Savior has been born to you&rdquo; (Luke 2:11) — the messengers bring the good news to those threatened. The men of Jabesh are overjoyed at the message before a single Ammonite has been struck — faith responding to the word of salvation before seeing the outcome. This is the NT structure of salvation: &ldquo;we were saved in this hope&rdquo; (Rom 8:24).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The men of Jabesh&rsquo;s deceptive compliance — &ldquo;tomorrow we will come out to you and you may do with us as you see fit&rdquo; — is tactical delay enabling the rescue. The theme of apparent surrender that conceals rescue resonates with Christ&rsquo;s &ldquo;yielding&rdquo; at the cross: he is apparently delivered over to the enemies&rsquo; power (&ldquo;do what you will&rdquo;), yet the apparent capitulation is the mechanism of ultimate deliverance. The surrendered city that is actually being rescued from within by an approaching king is the pattern of the Incarnation: Christ enters the besieged human condition not to be defeated by it but to rescue it from within.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The three-column night assault — an envelopment strategy striking before dawn — resulted in total victory: &ldquo;the survivors were so scattered that no two were left together.&rdquo; The three-direction military envelopment was the standard decisive engagement tactic in ancient warfare. Gideon&rsquo;s three-column night attack (Judg 7:16-22) used the same approach. The total scattering of the enemy — no two left together — is the complete defeat that holy war aimed at. Christ&rsquo;s victory over the powers of sin and death is the ultimate total defeat: &ldquo;having disarmed the powers and authorities, he made a public spectacle of them, triumphing over them by the cross&rdquo; (Col 2:15).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The people&rsquo;s demand after the victory — &ldquo;hand over those who said &lsquo;shall Saul reign over us&rsquo; so we can kill them&rdquo; — reveals the populist impulse to punish the dissenters now that the king has proved himself. The vindication of the king becomes the occasion for the people to demand vengeance on those who doubted. The pattern of the victorious king&rsquo;s followers seeking judgment on the dissenters anticipates the parable of the minas (Luke 19:27: &ldquo;bring those enemies of mine who did not want me to reign over them and kill them before me&rdquo;) — a scene of eschatological judgment deferred until the king returns. Saul&rsquo;s response in v13 transforms the demand for judgment into an occasion of mercy.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A type: Saul&rsquo;s declaration on the coronation day — &ldquo;no one shall be put to death today, for today the LORD has given Israel victory&rdquo; — is a shadow of the mercy shown by the messianic king at his enthronement. On the day of YHWH&rsquo;s salvation, the condemned are not executed but pardoned. The structural parallel with Christ is direct: at the cross (his coronation), the condemned criminal asks for mercy and receives it immediately (&ldquo;today you will be with me in paradise&rdquo;, Luke 23:43). The inaugural mercy of the king — sparing those who deserved punishment on the day of his vindication — is the pattern of messianic grace. It is not amnesia about the crime but deliberate royal mercy that exceeds justice.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Samuel&rsquo;s call to go to Gilgal to &ldquo;reaffirm the kingship there&rdquo; (<em>nəḥaddēš šām hamməlûkāh</em>) — renew or restore the kingship at the covenant site. Gilgal as the place of covenant renewal (circumcision renewed, Passover celebrated, Josh 5) is the appropriate site for the new king&rsquo;s installation. The renewing of covenant commitments at the site of first covenant-making is the structure of revival in both Testaments: renewal of the covenant under Josiah at the temple (2 Kgs 23), renewal of baptismal grace throughout the NT epistles. Christ&rsquo;s call to the seven churches (Rev 2-3) to repent and &ldquo;return to your first love&rdquo; (2:4-5) is the ultimate call to Gilgal — back to the beginning of covenant relationship.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The coronation at Gilgal: the whole people, peace offerings before YHWH, great rejoicing. The coronation feast is the fulfillment of the Deuteronomic covenant ideal — Israel rejoicing before YHWH with their king (Deut 12:12; 16:11). The peace offering (<em>šəlāmîm</em>) — shared between altar, priest, and worshippers — represents restored covenant fellowship, the shalom that the king&rsquo;s reign inaugurates. Christ&rsquo;s coronation culminates in the eschatological feast of Revelation 19:6-9: &ldquo;Let us rejoice and be glad and give him glory! For the wedding of the Lamb has come... Blessed are those who are invited to the wedding supper of the Lamb.&rdquo; What begins at Gilgal in limited form is completed at the Marriage Supper in fullness.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>Samuel&rsquo;s farewell address — &ldquo;I have listened to you in everything you asked of me and have set a king over you&rdquo; — is the transition speech of the judge-prophet handing over to the king. Samuel as the departing leader who has served faithfully and now installs his successor is a type of John the Baptist: &ldquo;he must become greater; I must become less&rdquo; (John 3:30). The prophetic forerunner gives way to the king. John explicitly names himself as the &ldquo;friend of the bridegroom&rdquo; (John 3:29) — his joy is complete when the king arrives and the prophetic office yields to its fulfillment.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Samuel&rsquo;s accounting of his life&rsquo;s service — &ldquo;I have served before you from my youth until this day&rdquo; — is the righteousness claim of the faithful servant who can present himself before YHWH and the people with integrity. The servant who has served faithfully from youth and now faces transition: this is the type of Christ as YHWH&rsquo;s servant who completes his commission and presents himself to the Father (John 17:4: &ldquo;I have brought you glory on earth by finishing the work you gave me to do&rdquo;). Samuel&rsquo;s old age stands in tension with Saul&rsquo;s youth — the faithful old gives way to the new, as the old covenant gives way to the new in Christ.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A type: Samuel&rsquo;s righteousness challenge — &ldquo;testify against me... have I defrauded anyone? oppressed anyone? taken a bribe?&rdquo; — is the challenge of perfect integrity. No accuser comes forward. Samuel&rsquo;s clean hands are a type of the righteousness that Christ alone can claim perfectly: &ldquo;can any of you prove me guilty of sin?&rdquo; (John 8:46). Before Pilate, the verdict is similarly &ldquo;I find no basis for a charge against him&rdquo; (John 18:38). The righteous judge who invites accusation and receives none is the pattern of the one who is &ldquo;holy, blameless, pure, set apart from sinners&rdquo; (Heb 7:26). Samuel&rsquo;s righteousness is genuine but limited; Christ&rsquo;s is absolute and atoning.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The people&rsquo;s testimony — &ldquo;you have not defrauded us, oppressed us, or taken anything from anyone&rdquo; — clears Samuel. The declaration of innocence by the people who were governed is the covenant community&rsquo;s attestation. The NT parallel: the disciples&rsquo; testimony to Christ&rsquo;s integrity (&ldquo;we have seen his glory&rdquo;, John 1:14), and the wider testimony that &ldquo;he committed no sin, and no deceit was found in his mouth&rdquo; (1 Pet 2:22, citing Isa 53:9). The community&rsquo;s attestation of the righteous leader&rsquo;s integrity is the human side of the divine declaration of righteousness.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD and his anointed are witnesses today&rdquo; — YHWH and the <em>māšîaḥ</em> together as witnesses. The pairing of YHWH and his anointed as co-witnesses is the OT formulation closest to the NT&rsquo;s identification of Father and Son as one: &ldquo;The Father and I are one&rdquo; (John 10:30); &ldquo;whoever has seen me has seen the Father&rdquo; (John 14:9). The anointed one shares YHWH&rsquo;s witness role — divine witness is not separated from the king&rsquo;s witness. Christ as both divine and human witness to the truth (&ldquo;I am the way, the truth...&rdquo;, John 14:6; &ldquo;for this reason I was born... to testify to the truth&rdquo;, John 18:37) fulfills what the pairing of YHWH and his anointed anticipates.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Samuel invokes YHWH who &ldquo;appointed Moses and Aaron&rdquo; — the divine author of all legitimate prophetic and priestly appointment. The claim that YHWH himself appointed Moses and Aaron rather than Israel&rsquo;s leaders choosing them establishes the principle of divine vocation versus human appointment. Christ&rsquo;s high priesthood is similarly validated: &ldquo;no one takes this honor on himself, but he receives it when called by God, just as Aaron was — and so Christ also did not take on himself the glory of becoming a high priest. But God said to him, &lsquo;You are my Son&rsquo;... you are a priest forever in the order of Melchizedek&rdquo; (Heb 5:4-6). The divine appointment of Moses and Aaron is the precedent for the divine appointment of Christ.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Samuel calls Israel to &ldquo;take your stand&rdquo; while he rehearses YHWH&rsquo;s righteous acts (<em>ṣidqôt YHWH</em> — the righteousness/justice-acts of YHWH). The recitation of divine <em>ṣidqôt</em> is the covenant lawsuit structure (the <em>rîb</em>): YHWH&rsquo;s covenant acts are rehearsed to measure Israel&rsquo;s response against them. Paul&rsquo;s argument in Romans similarly rehearses God&rsquo;s righteous acts (the covenant history of Abraham, Moses, and Christ) to establish the basis on which God declares sinners righteous. The <em>ṣidqôt YHWH</em> that Samuel recites in v7-11 are the type of the righteousness of God that is &ldquo;revealed from faith to faith&rdquo; in the gospel (Rom 1:17).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Exodus pattern — Jacob into Egypt, the cry, Moses and Aaron sent, deliverance and settlement — is the foundational salvation narrative that the rest of the OT elaborates and the NT fulfills. Samuel&rsquo;s rehearsal of this pattern frames the monarchy within the Exodus salvation: the king is YHWH&rsquo;s instrument for continuing the Exodus work. Christ is the new Moses who leads the new Exodus from sin and death (Heb 3:1-6 compares Moses and Christ directly; John 6:32-33 contrasts Moses&rsquo; manna with the true bread from heaven). The salvation history that begins with the Exodus of Jacob&rsquo;s family from Egypt reaches its terminus in Christ&rsquo;s exodus from the grave.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Israel&rsquo;s forgetting YHWH and being handed over to enemies — Sisera, the Philistines, Moab — is the Deuteronomic discipline cycle: forgetting → oppression → crying out → deliverance. This cycle runs throughout Judges and Samuel as the structure of covenant failure and grace. Paul describes the same structure in Romans 1:18-3:20: humanity forgot God, was given over to the consequences of that choice, and now cries out (3:9-20: &ldquo;no one is righteous&rdquo;) — the universal version of the judges cycle. Christ enters this cycle not as another judge but as the one who absorbs the full weight of &ldquo;being handed over&rdquo; (Rom 4:25: &ldquo;he was delivered over to death for our sins&rdquo;) to break the cycle permanently.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The confession formula — &ldquo;we have sinned; we forsook the LORD and served the Baals and the Ashtaroth&rdquo; — is the covenant-repentance cry that activates divine rescue. The sequence of forsaking → confession → &ldquo;deliver us now and we will serve you&rdquo; is the shape of repentance and return. Luke 15&rsquo;s prodigal son enacts precisely this: the son &ldquo;comes to himself&rdquo; (v17), confesses (&ldquo;I have sinned against heaven and against you&rdquo;, v18), and returns to the father. The father&rsquo;s response — running to meet him before the confession is finished — is the grace that the judges cycle of Samuel only hints at. In Christ, the Father does not wait for the confession but goes to meet the returning sinner.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The four deliverers YHWH sent — Jerubbaal (Gideon), Bedan, Jephthah, Samuel — form a series of imperfect deliverers who each partially fulfil the pattern of the promised deliverer. The accumulation of judges, each saving Israel in their generation, creates the expectation of one who will save permanently. Heb 11&rsquo;s &ldquo;hall of faith&rdquo; recounts these deliverers (Gideon, Barak, Samson, Jephthah, David, Samuel, the prophets) to establish that &ldquo;none of them received what had been promised, since God had planned something better for us so that only together with us would they be made perfect&rdquo; (Heb 11:39-40). All the judge-deliverers point beyond themselves to Christ, the permanent and final deliverer.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD your God was your king&rdquo; (<em>waYHWH ʾelōhêkem malkəkem</em>) — the theocratic claim that was rejected when Israel demanded a human king. The Psalms restore this claim: &ldquo;The LORD is king&rdquo; (Ps 99:1); &ldquo;The LORD, the Most High, is the great King over all the earth&rdquo; (Ps 47:2). Jesus comes preaching &ldquo;the kingdom of God is at hand&rdquo; (Mark 1:15) — the reinstatement of the rejected theocracy. John 19:14-15 frames the cross as the explicit rejection of YHWH&rsquo;s kingship: &ldquo;Here is your king!&rdquo; — &ldquo;we have no king but Caesar.&rdquo; The statement that YHWH was Israel&rsquo;s king is the constitution of the messianic kingdom that Christ comes to restore.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The conditional installation — &ldquo;here is the king you chose and asked for; the LORD has set a king over you&rdquo; — is the divine ratification of the people&rsquo;s request with the warning conditions attached. The king is simultaneously the people&rsquo;s choice and YHWH&rsquo;s appointment — the human will and divine sovereignty working together, as in all covenant narrative. Christ similarly comes as both the one Israel longed for (&ldquo;the consolation of Israel&rdquo;, Luke 2:25) and the one the Father sends (&ldquo;God so loved the world that he gave his one and only Son&rdquo;, John 3:16). The king given in response to a cry is given by divine will, not merely human wish.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The conditional covenant formula — &ldquo;if you fear the LORD and serve him and obey his voice... both you and the king who rules you will follow the LORD your God&rdquo; — states the ideal of the Davidic covenant: the king and the people together in covenantal faithfulness. The Psalms envision this ideal (Ps 72: the king who rules in justice and righteousness, under whom the people flourish). Christ fulfills the condition from both sides: as the true King he perfectly obeys the Father, and as the Head of the new covenant community he brings his people into that same obedience (&ldquo;the obedience of faith&rdquo;, Rom 1:5; 16:26). The conditional covenant is fulfilled unconditionally in Christ because he meets the condition on behalf of all.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The covenant curse — &ldquo;if you rebel against his command, the hand of the LORD will be against you, as it was against your ancestors&rdquo; — is the Deuteronomic judgment that follows covenant breach. The hand of the LORD against the people is the same power that delivered them (Deut 26:8: &ldquo;the LORD brought us out of Egypt with a mighty hand and an outstretched arm&rdquo;) when wielded in judgment rather than rescue. Christ absorbs the covenant curse: &ldquo;Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us — for it is written: Cursed is everyone who is hung on a pole&rdquo; (Gal 3:13, citing Deut 21:23). The hand that was against the covenant-breaker was laid on Christ, so that the hand of blessing might reach those who deserved the curse.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;Stand still and see the great thing the LORD is about to do before your eyes&rdquo; — the invitation to witness divine action. Samuel uses the same formula as Moses at the Red Sea (Exod 14:13: &ldquo;stand firm and you will see the deliverance the LORD will bring you today&rdquo;). The divine act about to be performed — unseasonable thunder and rain — is a sign of YHWH&rsquo;s sovereign power over creation. &ldquo;Stand still and see&rdquo; is the posture of faith: not acting in self-reliance but waiting to witness what YHWH will do. The ultimate expression of &ldquo;stand still and see&rdquo; is Easter morning: those who waited saw the great thing — the resurrection — that YHWH did.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Thunder and rain in wheat harvest — the dry season (May-June) when rain was virtually unknown in Palestine — is the unseasonable miracle that confirms Samuel&rsquo;s prophetic authority and the seriousness of Israel&rsquo;s sin. YHWH&rsquo;s authority over the agricultural calendar — the very principle of Baal worship, which Israel found attractive, was precisely control of rain and fertility — is demonstrated by the unseasonable rain. Christ&rsquo;s authority over creation (stilling the storm, Matt 8:23-27; walking on water, Matt 14:25) demonstrates the same divine sovereignty over natural forces. The question the disciples ask — &ldquo;what kind of man is this? even the winds and the waves obey him!&rdquo; (Matt 8:27) — is the same astonishment that Samuel&rsquo;s thunder-and-rain sign produced: &ldquo;all the people stood in great awe of the LORD and of Samuel&rdquo; (v18).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The people&rsquo;s response to the supernatural sign — &ldquo;all the people stood in deep awe of the LORD and of Samuel&rdquo; (<em>wayyîrəʾû kol-hāʿām məʾōd ʾet-YHWH wəʾet-šəmûʾēl</em>) — is the fear of YHWH that the covenant required. Samuel and YHWH share the people&rsquo;s fear-response, as Christ and the Father share the disciples&rsquo; reverence. After Christ stills the storm, the disciples worship (Matt 14:33); after the Transfiguration, they fall facedown in fear (Matt 17:6). The combination of awe for YHWH and for his representative — held together — is the OT framework for the NT&rsquo;s identification of Jesus with YHWH.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The people&rsquo;s fear-driven request — &ldquo;pray to the LORD your God for us so we won&rsquo;t die!&rdquo; — is the recognition that they need intercessory mediation. They cannot approach YHWH directly in their sin; they need the prophet&rsquo;s prayer. Samuel as intercessor for sinful Israel is the type of Christ&rsquo;s eternal intercession: &ldquo;therefore he is able to save completely those who come to God through him, because he always lives to intercede for them&rdquo; (Heb 7:25). The people confess (&ldquo;we have added to all our sins this evil of asking for a king&rdquo;) and ask for mediated access to God — the exact structure of the gospel: confession + mediator = access to divine grace.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Samuel&rsquo;s reassurance — &ldquo;do not be afraid. You have committed all this wrong, but do not turn away from the LORD — serve him with your whole heart&rdquo; — is the gospel word of grace after conviction: you have sinned, but the response is not self-punishment or distance from God but deeper engagement. &ldquo;Do not be afraid&rdquo; is the most repeated divine command in the Bible, and it is always spoken after the awareness of unworthiness in the presence of holiness (Isa 6:5-7; Luke 5:8-10; Rev 1:17). The Christ who says &ldquo;neither do I condemn you; go and sin no more&rdquo; (John 8:11) is the fulfillment of Samuel&rsquo;s &ldquo;do not be afraid — but serve him with your whole heart.&rdquo;</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;Do not turn away to pursue empty idols that cannot help or save — they are worthless&rdquo; (<em>hattōhû lōʾ yôʿîlû wəlōʾ yaṣṣîlû kî-tōhû hēm</em>) — <em>tōhû</em> (emptiness/void) is the word used for pre-creation chaos in Gen 1:2. Idols are the equivalent of pre-creation void — they offer the appearance of power and help but contain nothing. Isaiah extensively develops this theme (&ldquo;they are nothing&rdquo;, Isa 44:9; &ldquo;worthless&rdquo;, Isa 44:10; their makers are &ldquo;nothing&rdquo;, Isa 44:12). Christ&rsquo;s exclusive claim — &ldquo;no one comes to the Father except through me&rdquo; (John 14:6) — is the positive assertion of the truth that Samuel&rsquo;s negative warning anticipates: idols save nothing; YHWH in Christ saves everything.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;The LORD will not abandon his people, because of his great name — it pleased him to make you his own&rdquo; (<em>kî hôʾîl YHWH laʿăśôt ʾetkem lô ləʿām</em>). YHWH&rsquo;s faithfulness to his people is grounded not in their merit but in his own name and character — his own decision and delight in them. This is the deepest ground of election and perseverance: God keeps his people because of who he is, not because of what they have done. The NT expression is Rom 11:29: &ldquo;for God&rsquo;s gifts and his call are irrevocable,&rdquo; and John 10:28-29: &ldquo;no one can snatch them out of my hand... no one can snatch them out of my Father&rsquo;s hand.&rdquo; The security of the believer rests on YHWH&rsquo;s character, which is expressed fully in the faithful love of Christ.</p>",
    "23": "<p>A type: Samuel&rsquo;s intercessory commitment — &ldquo;far be it from me to sin against the LORD by stopping my prayers for you&rdquo; (<em>ḥālîlāh lî mēḥăṭōʾ la-YHWH meḥădal lehitpallēl baʿadkem</em>) — defines perpetual intercession as the ongoing work of the prophet. Samuel will continue to pray for Israel even as he hands over his public leadership role. Christ&rsquo;s perpetual intercession (Heb 7:25: &ldquo;he always lives to intercede&rdquo;; Rom 8:34: &ldquo;Christ Jesus... is at the right hand of God and is also interceding for us&rdquo;) is the fulfillment of Samuel&rsquo;s commitment. The prophet who refuses to stop praying for his people is the type of the High Priest whose intercessory work is eternal and unceasing.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The closing charge — &ldquo;only fear the LORD and serve him faithfully with all your heart — consider the great things he has done for you&rdquo; — is the distillation of covenant faithfulness: fear, service, wholehearted devotion, and remembrance. These four elements are the core of deuteronomic covenant life (Deut 6:4-9, 17; 10:12-13). Christ&rsquo;s summary of the law (Matt 22:37-39: love God with heart, soul, mind, and strength; love neighbor as self) is the positive fulfillment of this covenant charge. &ldquo;Consider the great things he has done for you&rdquo; — the memory of salvation as the motivation for obedience — is precisely the logic of 1 Cor 6:20: &ldquo;you were bought at a price; therefore honor God with your bodies.&rdquo;</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;But if you persist in doing evil, both you and your king will be swept away&rdquo; — the final covenant warning. The &ldquo;sweeping away&rdquo; (<em>tussāpû</em>) of both people and king together is the judgment that the disobedient covenant community brings on itself. The book of Samuel will enact this warning in slow motion: Saul&rsquo;s disobedience accumulates until he is swept away (ch31), and Israel&rsquo;s persistent unfaithfulness leads eventually to the exile. But the exile is not the end of the covenant story: the one who was swept away in the judgment (&ldquo;he was cut off from the land of the living&rdquo;, Isa 53:8) rises from that sweeping away to become the foundation of the new covenant community that cannot be swept away (&ldquo;on this rock I will build my church, and the gates of death will not overcome it&rdquo;, Matt 16:18).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', '1samuel')
    merge_comm(c, CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '1samuel', c)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in CHRIST.values())
    print(f'1 Samuel 9-12 mkt-christ written ({total} verses).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
